  "text": "This analysis identified 115 Java source files in the apache/kafka repository that use the ConfigKey and ConfigDef pattern for configuration documentation. While technically not Java annotations, these classes implement a declarative configuration pattern that serves the same metadata documentation and validation purposes.\n\nThe pattern centers around two core classes in the org.apache.kafka.common.config package:\n1. ConfigDef - A builder class for defining configuration specifications with metadata (type, default value, documentation, validators, importance, etc.)\n2. ConfigKey - A static inner class in ConfigDef representing individual configuration entries with all their metadata\n\nKey findings include:\n\nCORE CONFIGURATION FRAMEWORK (17 files):\nThe foundation is in clients/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/common/config/, containing ConfigDef.java and AbstractConfig.java. ConfigDef provides the declarative API for defining configurations, while AbstractConfig is the base class that all configuration classes extend. Supporting classes handle exceptions, transformations, and providers.\n\nDOCUMENTATION GENERATORS (2 files):\nPredicateDoc.java and TransformationDoc.java in connect/runtime/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/connect/tools/ demonstrate the pattern's documentation capability. These tools reflect on CONFIG_DEF static fields and use ConfigDef.toHtml() methods to generate comprehensive HTML documentation automatically.\n\nABSTRACTCONFIG SUBCLASSES (78+ files):\nThe pattern is used extensively throughout Kafka:\n- Clients module: AdminClientConfig, ConsumerConfig, ProducerConfig\n- Kafka Connect: ConnectorConfig, TaskConfig, WorkerConfig, DistributedConfig, StandaloneConfig, various converter and transformation configs\n- Kafka Server: ServerConfigs, SocketServerConfigs, KRaftConfigs, ReplicationConfigs, MetricConfigs\n- Kafka Streams: StreamsConfig, TopologyConfig, AssignmentConfigs\n- Coordinators: GroupCoordinatorConfig, TransactionStateManagerConfig, QuorumConfig\n- Storage: LogConfig, RemoteLogManagerConfig\n\nSUPPORTING UTILITIES (18 files):\nIncludes ConfigInfo/ConfigKeyInfo REST entity representations, ConfigUtils helper methods, and ConnectorPluginsResource which exposes configuration metadata via REST API.\n\nThe pattern enables Kafka components to declaratively define their configuration schemas with full metadata, which is then used for:\n- Type-safe configuration parsing and validation\n- Automatic HTML documentation generation\n- REST API exposure of configuration schemas\n- Reflection-based configuration introspection"
}

